	<entry>
		<title type="html"><![CDATA[Re: Some confusions about translations of Sanskrit mantras]]></title>
		<link rel="alternate" href="http://spokensanskrit.de/board/forum/viewtopic.php?pid=4645#p4645"/>
		<content type="html"><![CDATA[<div class="quotebox"><cite>theunborn wrote:</cite><blockquote><div><p>These English transliterations are wrong and are based on Hindi pronunciation of Devanagari script.&#160; The web site that is putting out these mantras has no idea how to pronounce Sanskrit.<br />Sorry for being blunt. But there are so many of these in the internet and I cannot think of a good suggestion/idea/advice I could offer you here.</p></div></blockquote></div><p>I thought you might say you got the translator of this site at least... I mean copy and paste the Sanskrit into the translation bar and the result comes out. But now a new problem occurs. Some Sanskrit mantras are shown in picture/JPEG format and can not be copied/pasted into the translation bar of this site. What can do I do about this? Any good idea or suggestion? Thanks in advance.</p>]]></content>
		<author>
			<name><![CDATA[photoarman]]></name>
			<uri>http://spokensanskrit.de/board/forum/profile.php?id=8569</uri>
		</author>
		<updated>2013-03-04T17:33:31Z</updated>
		<id>http://spokensanskrit.de/board/forum/viewtopic.php?pid=4645#p4645</id>
	</entry>
	<entry>
		<title type="html"><![CDATA[Re: Some confusions about translations of Sanskrit mantras]]></title>
		<link rel="alternate" href="http://spokensanskrit.de/board/forum/viewtopic.php?pid=4644#p4644"/>
		<content type="html"><![CDATA[<p>These English transliterations are wrong and are based on Hindi pronunciation of Devanagari script.&#160; The web site that is putting out these mantras has no idea how to pronounce Sanskrit.<br />Sorry for being blunt. But there are so many of these in the internet and I cannot think of a good suggestion/idea/advice I could offer you here.</p>]]></content>
		<author>
			<name><![CDATA[theunborn]]></name>
			<uri>http://spokensanskrit.de/board/forum/profile.php?id=228</uri>
		</author>
		<updated>2013-03-04T14:42:32Z</updated>
		<id>http://spokensanskrit.de/board/forum/viewtopic.php?pid=4644#p4644</id>
	</entry>
	<entry>
		<title type="html"><![CDATA[Re: Some confusions about translations of Sanskrit mantras]]></title>
		<link rel="alternate" href="http://spokensanskrit.de/board/forum/viewtopic.php?pid=4603#p4603"/>
		<content type="html"><![CDATA[<div class="quotebox"><cite>Alex wrote:</cite><blockquote><div><p>ॐ देव ममो हरय ठ ठ स्वाहा should be pronounced this way:</p><p>om deva namo haraya tha tha svaha</p><p>Alex</p></div></blockquote></div><p>Alex Sir,<br />Thanks for the reply. The missing letters like &quot;a&quot; confuse me and decrease my faith in mantra chanting. I can give more examples like this:</p><p>Om Namah shivaya- this is what I see most of the time.</p><p>Om Namah shivay- Now I found this in Google ToolBar. Because this mantra very common, I can conclude that these two are indeed the same. But look at the mantra below:</p><p>Kleeng Kamdevay Namah</p><p>Is it same case as the mantra above? I mean it should be pronounced as &quot;Kamdevaya&quot; instead of Kam-de-wai(like the &quot;ai&quot; in Thailand in English)? There&#039;re many cases like this and I need to figure it out. Thanks in advance.</p>]]></content>
		<author>
			<name><![CDATA[photoarman]]></name>
			<uri>http://spokensanskrit.de/board/forum/profile.php?id=8569</uri>
		</author>
		<updated>2013-03-03T13:23:59Z</updated>
		<id>http://spokensanskrit.de/board/forum/viewtopic.php?pid=4603#p4603</id>
	</entry>
	<entry>
		<title type="html"><![CDATA[Re: Some confusions about translations of Sanskrit mantras]]></title>
		<link rel="alternate" href="http://spokensanskrit.de/board/forum/viewtopic.php?pid=4595#p4595"/>
		<content type="html"><![CDATA[<p>ॐ देव ममो हरय ठ ठ स्वाहा should be pronounced this way:</p><p>om deva namo haraya tha tha svaha</p><p>Alex</p>]]></content>
		<author>
			<name><![CDATA[Alex]]></name>
			<uri>http://spokensanskrit.de/board/forum/profile.php?id=293</uri>
		</author>
		<updated>2013-03-02T20:53:23Z</updated>
		<id>http://spokensanskrit.de/board/forum/viewtopic.php?pid=4595#p4595</id>
	</entry>
	<entry>
		<title type="html"><![CDATA[Re: Some confusions about translations of Sanskrit mantras]]></title>
		<link rel="alternate" href="http://spokensanskrit.de/board/forum/viewtopic.php?pid=4566#p4566"/>
		<content type="html"><![CDATA[<div class="quotebox"><cite>theunborn wrote:</cite><blockquote><div><p>Devanagari script is used not only by Sanskrit but also by a few other languages in India. Particularly, in Hindi language the trailing vowel is removed from most words (you can see http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Schwa_deletion_in_Indo-Aryan_languages for details).</p><p>So, if a person, who uses any of these languages but not familiar with how Sanskrit is pronounced, is going to transliterate Sanskrit incorrectly. This is one of those cases.</p></div></blockquote></div><p>Unborn Sir,<br />I don&#039;t quite understand your point but your information is appreciated. Now as per the Sanskrit mantra I mentioned above, &quot;deva&quot; and &quot;tha&quot; are correct romanized translations of देव and ठ, right? I only need to know how to pronounce them correctly because understanding too much about their meanings may affect a sadhak&#039;s concentration while reciting them. Without a vowel like &quot;a&quot;, I don&#039;t know how to pronounce it because words like &quot;dev&quot; or &quot;th&quot; do NOT happen in English. This is my true confusion in this topic.</p>]]></content>
		<author>
			<name><![CDATA[photoarman]]></name>
			<uri>http://spokensanskrit.de/board/forum/profile.php?id=8569</uri>
		</author>
		<updated>2013-03-02T07:55:09Z</updated>
		<id>http://spokensanskrit.de/board/forum/viewtopic.php?pid=4566#p4566</id>
	</entry>
	<entry>
		<title type="html"><![CDATA[Re: Some confusions about translations of Sanskrit mantras]]></title>
		<link rel="alternate" href="http://spokensanskrit.de/board/forum/viewtopic.php?pid=4385#p4385"/>
		<content type="html"><![CDATA[<p>Devanagari script is used not only by Sanskrit but also by a few other languages in India. Particularly, in Hindi language the trailing vowel is removed from most words (you can see http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Schwa_deletion_in_Indo-Aryan_languages for details).</p><p>So, if a person, who uses any of these languages but not familiar with how Sanskrit is pronounced, is going to transliterate Sanskrit incorrectly. This is one of those cases.</p>]]></content>
		<author>
			<name><![CDATA[theunborn]]></name>
			<uri>http://spokensanskrit.de/board/forum/profile.php?id=228</uri>
		</author>
		<updated>2013-02-25T10:28:14Z</updated>
		<id>http://spokensanskrit.de/board/forum/viewtopic.php?pid=4385#p4385</id>
	</entry>
	<entry>
		<title type="html"><![CDATA[Some confusions about translations of Sanskrit mantras]]></title>
		<link rel="alternate" href="http://spokensanskrit.de/board/forum/viewtopic.php?pid=4378#p4378"/>
		<content type="html"><![CDATA[<p>Mantra<br />Om dev mamo haray th th swaha ll</p><p>मंत्र<br />ॐ देव ममो हरय ठ ठ स्वाहा</p><p>Like my previous post, this is from the same site. You can see the letter &quot;a&quot; keep missing. What confuses me is that, if it is just a typo, why it happens again and again(and it&#039;s&#160; always the letter &quot;a&quot; that is missing)? As shown above, it seems that &quot;a&quot; is always missing in the mantra, like &quot;dev&quot; and &quot;th&quot;, and I don&#039;t know how to pronounce these two without the letter &quot;a&quot;. But I have no problem pronouncing &quot;deva&quot; and &quot;tha&quot;. </p><p>The same thing happens everywhere on the net. Like &quot;shiva guru mantra&quot;, you may see it shown as &quot;shiv guru mantra&quot; in Google Search. Or the word सर्व, I saw it translated as &quot;sarv&quot; in the romanized version of the mantra on the same site. Again its the letter a missing. Is it simply a typo? I&#039;m confused. Anyone please help me with this confusion. Thanks a lot.</p>]]></content>
